      "id":"commentisfree/emma-brockes-blog/2013/oct/17/kate-winslet-vogue-cover-grotesque",
      "sectionId":"commentisfree",
      "sectionName":"Comment is free",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-10-17T16:12:00Z",
      "webTitle":"Kate Winslet's Vogue cover is ageless. But not in a good way | Emma Brockes",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/emma-brockes-blog/2013/oct/17/kate-winslet-vogue-cover-grotesque",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/commentisfree/emma-brockes-blog/2013/oct/17/kate-winslet-vogue-cover-grotesque",
      "fields":{
        "trailText":"<p><strong>Emma Brockes:</strong> Hollywood is famously unkind to leading ladies of a certain age, but this is the reverse: Testino's airbrushed portrait is sycophancy</p>",
        "headline":"Kate Winslet's Vogue cover is ageless. But not in a good way",
        "body":"<p>Kate Winslet is on the <a href=\"http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/10/14/kate-winslet-vogue-photos_n_4096789.html\">cover of this month's Vogue</a> and the photo is unbelievable.</p><p>I mean, literally unbelievable. The 38-year-old, who does OK without <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2012/oct/21/mario-testino-interview-fashion-photography\">Mario Testino's</a> help, looks in this portrait like a CGI version of herself. Her hair is detachable plastic; her eyes are like marbles. Her expression, which I guess is her own, albeit under Testino's direction, is sort of mysterious with a touch of, \"Help! I've been laminated!\"</p><p>It is abominably, thrillingly awful.</p><p>Like the plastic surgery debate, the airbrushing debate never gets us anywhere. Who, given the kind of scrutiny these women fall under, wouldn't beg and plead for a little help from the art department? Not that they need much encouraging. It's a catch-22: the movie and beauty industries won't change until older women are more visible, but older women don't want to be visible until the industries change. (And by older, obviously, I mean post-34.)</p><p>Who can blame them? You could probably mount a <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2013/sep/29/malcolm-gladwell-david-and-goliath-interview\">Malcolm Gladwell-type argument</a> that, like drug use in sport, women movie stars should be allowed to use any resources available to them, to level the playing field against the God-given gifts of youth and symmetry. It puts the rest of us under pressure, of course, and trickles down into all sorts of considerations, but there comes a point in life when you understand you aren't a movie star and move on. Honestly, good luck to them.</p><figure data-media-id='gu-image-420337962'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/10/15/1381873870653/katewinsletvogue-496x620.jpg' alt='Kate Winslet Vogue Cover' width='460' height='620' class='gu-image'/><figcaption>Winslet on the cover of November's issue of Vogue. Photograph: guardian.co.uk</figcaption></figure><p>In this case, the Vogue cover will probably end up doing us all favour, since it's so blatantly, revealingly ludicrous. Testino, whose job I recall seeing described once as being that of making beautiful people look more beautiful, has always produced crashingly boring portraits, which kitsch out every last shred of his subjects' humanity. Say what you like about Annie Leibovitz, at least she brings props.</p><p>The actual interview with Winslet, on the other hand, is quite good. She defends her right to have three children by three different fathers and, sounding like Edith Evans, says briskly:</p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>[M]y kids don't go back and forth; none of this 50/50 time with the mums and dads. My children live with me; that is it. That is it!</p></blockquote><p>It's the kind of quote that, if you're not careful, will land you a <a href=\"http://www.somersetcountygazette.co.uk/news/taunton_news/10693454.One_arrested_after_Fathers4Justice__Spiderman__ends_Taunton_bridge_protest/\">guy in a Spiderman suit</a> with a Fathers 4 Justice placard on your doorstep.</p><p>Perhaps, the Barbie-like cover shot will repel people; perhaps, there will be enough outrage to provoke Winslet to respond, as she did after she was airbrushed on the <a href=\"http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/2643777.stm\">cover of GQ</a> ten years ago. Though, that was slightly different, since weight was a factor and Winslet has always campaigned about size-ism.</p><p>But this is ageism: they've stripped the lines from her face, and, at 38, she is entering the danger zone for actresses and is probably inclined to capitulate. (On point, I saw a preview of a new biopic of Dickens last week, in which Ralph Fiennes plays the hero and Kristin Scott Thomas, his former leading lady from The English Patient, plays <em>the mother</em> of his mistress.)</p><p>The best response to the Vogue cover is to laugh: the magazine is so far out to sea at this point, it has no sense of how transparent its manipulations are. It's like the inverse of Dorian Grey – as the portraits on the cover get more and more \"perfect\", the body of the product gets ever more sickly. You almost wonder if, as in Spike Jonze's new movie, Her, it is making a <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/filmblog/2013/sep/09/spike-jonze-her-scarlett-johansson\">satirical point about realism</a>, although neither satire nor point-making is quite the magazine's style. Its style, this month at least, is flat and fake, a fantasy that fails on its own terms.</p><p>The grotesque can be beautiful, but not here.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/420070199|2013-10-18T10:47:05Z|360d98083ca04184b538a8fe6ac5e26e9bb3c758 -->",
